# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apk-alpine-packaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/alpine-linux] Originally, Alpine Linux began as an embedded-first distribution for devices such as wireless routers, based on Gentoo Linux, inspired by GNAP and the Bering-uClibc branch of the LEAF Project.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/alpine-linux] Founder Natanael Copa has said that the name was chosen as a backronym for "A Linux-Powered Network Engine" or some such similar phrase, but that the exact phrase has since been forgotten.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/alpine-linux] Alpine's package management system, the Alpine Package Keeper (apk), was originally a collection of shell scripts but was later rewritten in C.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/alpine-linux] In 2014, Alpine Linux switched from uClibc to musl as its C standard library.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/alpine-linux] postmarketOS, a Linux distribution for mobile devices, is based on Alpine Linux.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] The **Android Package** with the file extension **apk** is a package format used by Android and a number of other Android-based operating systems for distribution and installation of mobile apps, mobile games and middleware.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] A file using this format can be built from source code written in either Java or Kotlin.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] APK files can be generated and signed from Android App Bundles.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] APK is analogous to other software packages such as APPX in Microsoft Windows, APP for HarmonyOS or a Debian package in Debian-based operating systems.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] To make an APK file, a program for Android is first compiled using a tool such as Android Studio or Visual Studio and then all of its parts are packaged into one container file.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] An APK file contains all of a program's code (such as .dex files), resources, assets, certificates, and manifest file.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] As is the case with many file formats, APK files can have any desired name but, for the system to recognize them, the .apk filename suffix may be necessary.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] Most Android implementations allow users to manually install APK files (sideloading) only after they turn on an "Unknown Sources" setting that allows installation from sources other than trusted ones such as Google Play.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] This may be done for many reasons, such as during the development of apps, to install apps not available on the store, or to install an older version of an app in the Play Store.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] In 2026, Google announced that the "Unknown sources" toggle will be replaced with a process that involves enabling developer mode and a 24-hour pause before allowing sideloading from unverified developers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] Verification requires an identity document and $25 payment.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] The QNX-based BlackBerry 10 included an Android runtime environment; initially, apps were required to be packaged in the operating system's native format, and installed via the BlackBerry World app store or sideloading.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] Beginning on BlackBerry 10.2.1, the operating system added support for sideloading APK files directly.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] Google Mobile Services and certain core APIs would not be available, and apps with "deep integration into background tasks" were said to poorly support the environment.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] Portions of Astoria were used as a basis for Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) on the PC version of Windows 10.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] In June 2021, Microsoft announced the "Windows Subsystem for Android" (WSA), an AOSP-based layer for sideloading Android apps on Windows 11.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] The software utilized a runtime compiler developed by Intel, and apps could be sideloaded, published via Microsoft Store, or obtained via an Amazon Appstore client.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/apk-file-format] Microsoft deprecated and discontinued WSA in March 2025.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Originally written by Bruce Perens in 1995 and declared complete for his intended usage in 1996, BusyBox initially aimed to put a complete bootable system on a single floppy disk that would serve both as a rescue disk and as an installer for the Debian distribution.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Since that time, it has been extended to become the de facto standard core user space toolset for embedded Linux devices and Linux distribution installers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Since each Linux executable requires several kilobytes of overhead, having the BusyBox program combine over two hundred programs together often saves substantial disk space and system memory.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox was maintained by Enrique Zanardi and focused on the needs of the Debian boot-floppies installer system until early 1998, when Dave Cinege took it over for the Linux Router Project (LRP).
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Cinege made several additions, created a modularized build environment, and shifted BusyBox's focus into general high-level embedded systems.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] As LRP development slowed down in 1999, Erik Andersen, then of Lineo, Inc., took over the project and became the official maintainer between December 1999 and March 2006.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] During this time the Linux embedded marketplace exploded in growth, and BusyBox matured greatly, expanding both its user base and functionality.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Rob Landley became the maintainer in 2005 until late 2006, then Denys Vlasenko took over as the current maintainer.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] In September 2006, after heavy discussions and controversies between project maintainer Rob Landley and Bruce Perens, the BusyBox project decided against adopting the GNU General Public License Version 3 (GPLv3), and announced an intent to have the BusyBox license be GPLv2-only.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Since October 2006, Denys Vlasenko has taken over maintainership of BusyBox from Rob Landley, who has started Toybox, also as a result of the license controversies.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] In late 2007, BusyBox also came to prominence for actively prosecuting violations of the terms of its license (the GPL) in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] What was claimed to be the first US lawsuit over a GPL violation concerned the use of BusyBox in an embedded device.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The lawsuit, case 07-CV-8205, was filed on September 20, 2007, by the Software Freedom Law Center (SFLC) on behalf of Andersen and Landley against Monsoon Multimedia Inc., after BusyBox code was discovered in a firmware upgrade and attempts to contact the company had apparently failed.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The case was settled with release of the Monsoon version of the source and payment of an undisclosed amount of money to Andersen and Landley.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] On November 21, 2007, the SFLC brought two similar lawsuits on behalf of Andersen and Landley against two more companies, Xterasys (case 07-CV-10455) and High-Gain Antennas (case 07-CV-10456).
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The Xterasys case was settled on December 17 for release of source code used and an undisclosed payment, and the High-Gain Antennas case on March 6, 2008, for active license compliance and an undisclosed payment.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Further suits were brought on June 9, 2008, against Bell Microproducts (case 08-CV-5270) and SuperMicro (case 08-CV-5269), with the Super Micro case being settled on July 23, 2008.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox and Bell Microproducts also settled out of court on October 17.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] On December 14, 2009, a new lawsuit was filed naming fourteen defendants including Best Buy, JVC, Samsung and others.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] In February 2010 Samsung released its LN52A650 TV firmware under GPLv2, which was used later as a reference by the SamyGO community project.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] On about August 3, 2010, BusyBox won from Westinghouse a default judgement of triple damages of $90,000 and lawyers' costs and fees of $47,865, and possession of "presumably a lot of high-def TVs" as infringing equipment in the lawsuit Software Freedom Conservancy v.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Best Buy, et al., the GPL infringement case noted in the paragraph above.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] No other developers, including original author Bruce Perens and maintainer Dave Cinege, were represented in these actions or party to the settlements.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Toybox was started early 2006 under the GPL-2.0-only license by former BusyBox maintainer Rob Landley as a result of the controversies around GPLv3/GPLv2 discussions.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] At the end of 2011 it was relicensed under the BSD-2-Clause license after the project went dormant.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] In March 2013, it was relicensed again under the 0BSD license.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] On January 11, 2012, Tim Bird, a Sony employee, suggested creating an alternative to BusyBox which would not be under the GNU General Public License.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] He suggested it be based on the dormant Toybox.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] In January 2012 the proposal of creating a BSD licensed alternative to the GPL licensed BusyBox project drew harsh criticism from Matthew Garrett for taking away the only relevant tool for copyright enforcement of the Software Freedom Conservancy group.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The starter of BusyBox based lawsuits, Rob Landley, responded that this was intentional as he came to the conclusion that the lawsuits resulted not in the hoped for positive outcomes and he wanted to stop them "in whatever way I see fit".
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox can be customized to provide a subset of over two hundred utilities.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] It can provide most of the utilities specified in the Single Unix Specification (SUS) plus many others that a user would expect to see on a Linux system.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox uses the Almquist shell, also known as A Shell, ash and sh.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] An alternative for customization is the smaller 'hush' shell.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] As it is a complete bootstrap system, it will further replace the init daemon and udev (or the latter-day systemd) using itself to be called as *init* on startup and *mdev* at hotplug time.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The BusyBox website provides a full list of the utilities implemented.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Typical computer programs have a separate binary (executable) file for each application.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox is a single binary, which is a conglomerate of many applications, each of which can be accessed by calling the single BusyBox binary with various names (supported by having a symbolic link or hard link for each different name) in a specific manner with appropriate arguments.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Sharing of the common code, along with routines written with size-optimization in mind, can make a BusyBox system use much less storage space than a system built with the corresponding full versions of the utilities replaced by BusyBox.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Research that compared GNU, BusyBox, asmutils and Perl implementations of the standard Unix commands showed that in some situations BusyBox may perform faster than other implementations, but not always.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The official BusyBox documentation lists an overview of the available commands and their command-line options.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] A command can be run by prefixing a command line with a path to the BusyBox executable.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] Commonly, each command is exposed as a hard or symbolic link to the BusyBox executable.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] For example, if `/bin/ls` links to `/bin/busybox` then the program name command-line argument is "/bin/ls" and BusyBox treats it as the `ls` command.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox is used by several operating systems running on embedded systems and is an essential component of distributions such as OpenWrt, OpenEmbedded (including the Yocto Project) and Buildroot.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] The Sharp Zaurus utilizes BusyBox extensively for ordinary Unix-like tasks performed on the system's shell.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] BusyBox is also an essential component of VMware ESXi, Tiny Core Linux, SliTaz 5(Rolling), and Alpine Linux, none of which are embedded distributions.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/busybox] It is necessary for several root applications on Android and is also preinstalled with some "1 Tap Root" solutions such as Kingo Root.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] musl was designed from scratch to allow efficient static linking and to have realtime-quality robustness by avoiding race conditions, internal failures on resource exhaustion, and various other bad worst-case behaviors present in existing implementations.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] The dynamic runtime is a single file with stable ABI allowing race-free updates and the static linking support allows an application to be deployed as a single portable binary without significant size overhead.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] It claims compatibility with the POSIX 2008 specification and the C11 standard.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] It also implements most of the widely used non-standard Linux, BSD, and glibc functions.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] There is partial ABI compatibility with the part of glibc required by Linux Standard Base.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] A modified version of musl is available for userspace code written for the seL4 microkernel, requiring users to implement the parts of the Linux system call interface that the subset of musl they wish to use depends on.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] Huawei's HarmonyOS NEXT operating system uses a fork of musl as its libc implementation.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/musl] For binaries that have been linked against glibc, gcompat and glibmus-hq can be used to execute them on musl-based distros.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:apk-alpine-packaging/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
